To change the menu bar icon programmatically from `toggleInputMode()`, stop relying on SwiftUI’s `MenuBarExtra(systemImage:)` refresh and keep a reference to an AppKit status item/button instead.

However, with SwiftUI `MenuBarExtra`, Apple does not expose a clean API to mutate its underlying `NSStatusItem` directly. If you want imperative icon control inside `toggleInputMode()`, the straightforward route is to switch the menu bar item to AppKit `NSStatusItem`, like the prototype.

## AppKit status item approach

Add this property:

```swift
private var statusItem: NSStatusItem?
```

Create the status item during launch:

```swift
func applicationDidFinishLaunching(_ notification: Notification) {
    print("Activated.")
    installSignalHandler(SIGINT)
    installSignalHandler(SIGTERM)
    initializeEngineState()
    setupMenuBar()
    registerToggleInputModeHotKey()
    // Start event tap.
}
```

Add:

```swift
@MainActor
private func setupMenuBar() {
    let statusItem = NSStatusBar.system.statusItem(withLength: NSStatusItem.variableLength)
    self.statusItem = statusItem

    updateMenuBarIcon()

    let menu = NSMenu()
    menu.addItem(NSMenuItem(title: "Lock inputs", action: nil, keyEquivalent: ""))
    menu.addItem(NSMenuItem.separator())
    menu.addItem(NSMenuItem(title: "Quit", action: #selector(NSApplication.terminate(_:)), keyEquivalent: "q"))
    statusItem.menu = menu
}
```

Then update the icon imperatively:

```swift
@MainActor
private func updateMenuBarIcon() {
    guard let button = statusItem?.button else {
        return
    }

    let imageName = appState.mode == .telex
        ? "character.textbox.badge.sparkles"
        : "textformat.size.smaller"

    button.image = NSImage(
        systemSymbolName: imageName,
        accessibilityDescription: "Lex"
    )
}
```

Then call it from your toggle:

```swift
@MainActor
private func toggleInputMode() {
    appState.mode = appState.mode == .telex ? .literal : .telex

    updateMenuBarIcon()

    // TODO: this flow must change when finish integrating with engine.
    toggleInputModeSound?.stop()
    let soundName: NSSound.Name = appState.mode == .telex ? "Pop" : "Tink"
    toggleInputModeSound = NSSound(named: soundName)
    toggleInputModeSound?.play()
}
```

## Important: do not keep both menu bar systems

If you use `NSStatusItem`, remove or stop using this SwiftUI scene:

```swift
MenuBarExtra(...)
```

Otherwise the app may show two menu bar items.

Your `LexApp` body would become something minimal like:

```swift
var body: some Scene {
    Settings {
        EmptyView()
    }
}
```

or, if you do not need settings:

```swift
var body: some Scene {
    WindowGroup {
        EmptyView()
            .frame(width: 0, height: 0)
    }
}
```

But for a pure menu bar/accessory app, the prototype-style fully AppKit setup is cleaner.

## If you want to keep SwiftUI `MenuBarExtra`

Then I would not recommend imperative icon mutation. Instead, make the icon state-driven through an observed label view:

```swift
MenuBarExtra {
    LexMenu(
        appDelegate: appDelegate,
        appState: appDelegate.appState
    )
} label: {
    Image(systemName: appDelegate.appState.mode == .telex
        ? "character.textbox.badge.sparkles"
        : "textformat.size.smaller"
    )
}
```

But this still depends on SwiftUI refreshing correctly. It is not truly “programmatic” from `toggleInputMode()`.

## Minimal imperative function

If you switch to AppKit status item, the function you want is this:

```swift
@MainActor
private func updateMenuBarIcon() {
    let imageName = appState.mode == .telex
        ? "character.textbox.badge.sparkles"
        : "textformat.size.smaller"

    statusItem?.button?.image = NSImage(
        systemSymbolName: imageName,
        accessibilityDescription: "Lex"
    )
}
```

Call it immediately after changing `appState.mode`.

